sec.p:
With apartheid on the verge of collapse, in the late-1980s, South Africa was a country fecund with Marxist debate and it seemed plausible that the country’s future would be speeded by two developments in this direction. The first was the strong socialist current that ran through an increasingly confident trade union movement. Secondly, throughout the 1980s local affiliates of the UDF had established street-level cell structures (called street committees
4
) in urban black townships which were strongly inclined to employ Marxist rhetoric. These factors suggested the potential, if not the reality, of a competing national ideology and a series of dual-power organs which, themselves, pre-figured post-apartheid forms of radical democratic practice. Certainly, the scene seemed set for exciting times under post-apartheid conditions in which, surely, social transformation would have to be a national priority. There were also grounds for believing that, notwithstanding the collapse of the Soviet system and the deepening appeal of neo-liberal economics, the international community would be comfortable with a post-apartheid state pursuing – at the very least – a path of social democratic development with an eye to redressing the historical legacy of inequality and social injustice.
